<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-451-227  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 451 227.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>LAN Times  Sept 3 1990 v7 n10 p18(10).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Choosing LAN hardware; weighing system components can help you getbetter performance. (local area networks)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Corrigan, Patrick H.; Guy, Aisling.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The components of a local area network (LAN) must be balanced toachieve optimum performance for the money spent.andP;  There are threeprimary choices to make for a personal computer LAN: cabling, LANhardware, and LAN operating systems; usually, company requirementshelp make these choices.andP;  Factors to consider when selecting LANhardware are performance, LAN operating system and protocolsupport; adherence to standards; and vendor stability.andP;  LANperformance can be affected by the cable access method, raw datatransfer rate, and the network interface card.andP;  The LAN hardwaredetermines the choice of cabling.andP;  The file server, the heart ofthe personal computer LAN, must have enough processing power tohandle the tasks and have sufficient expansion capability tohandle any required network interface cards, RAM expansion boards,and other required hardware.andP;  Performance is the main criterionwhen selecting the workstations.andP;  Backup can be handled byhigh-capacity floppy disks, tape, or optical drives.andP;  Power backupand conditioning systems are needed.andP;  Measuring productivity gainsis the best way to benchmark LAN performance in an officeenvironment.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Local Area NetworksNetwork ManagementPerformanceHardware Selection.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>